    content: {
      rendered:
        '\u003Cdiv class="wp-block-image"\u003E\n\u003Cfigure class="aligncenter size-full"\u003E\u003Cimg loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="729" src="https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/KMRT-.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-335364" srcset="https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/KMRT-.jpg 1024w, https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/KMRT--300x214.jpg 300w, https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/KMRT--768x547.jpg 768w, https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/KMRT--205x146.jpg 205w, https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/KMRT--350x250.jpg 350w, https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/KMRT--120x86.jpg 120w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /\u003E\u003Cfigcaption class="wp-element-caption"\u003EPicture: Keswick Mountain Rescue Team \u003C/figcaption\u003E\u003C/figure\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\n\n\n\u003Cp\u003EKeswick Mountain Rescue Team was called after a cockerpoo got stuck on a ledge. \u003C/p\u003E\n\n\n\n\u003Cp\u003EThe team was called today, Sunday December 22, to Caldbeck at around 1.35pm. \u003C/p\u003E\n\n\n\n\u003Cp\u003EThe team said: &#8221; The cockapoo had managed to get itself stuck on a ledge several metres above a beck. \u003C/p\u003E\n\n\n\n\u003Cp\u003E&#8220;The owners tried to get to the dog but wisely considered it too risky so called for help. \u003C/p\u003E\n\n\n\n\u003Cp\u003E&#8220;A small team made their way upstream from Caldbeck village, rigged a rope rescue system and lowered a team member to the dog. \u003C/p\u003E\n\n\n\n\u003Cp\u003E&#8220;After securing the dog the team raised rescuer and dog a short distance back up to the path where the animal was happily reunited with its owner.&#8221;\u003C/p\u003E\n',
      protected: false,
    },
