    slug: 'illegal-scrap-dealer-fined-for-operating-without-licence',
    status: 'publish',
    type: 'post',
    link: 'https://cumbriacrack.com/2024/12/18/illegal-scrap-dealer-fined-for-operating-without-licence/',
    title: { rendered: 'Illegal scrap dealer fined for operating without licence' },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '<div class="wp-block-image">\n<figure class="aligncenter size-full"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="690" src="https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/Workington-magistrates-court-4-1024x690-1.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-248446" srcset="https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/Workington-magistrates-court-4-1024x690-1.jpg 1024w, https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/Workington-magistrates-court-4-1024x690-1-300x202.jpg 300w, https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/Workington-magistrates-court-4-1024x690-1-768x518.jpg 768w, https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/Workington-magistrates-court-4-1024x690-1-217x146.jpg 217w, https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/Workington-magistrates-court-4-1024x690-1-750x505.jpg 750w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>A man has admitted collecting scrap metal without a licence and been fined by magistrates. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Robert Dixon, 57, of Sheffield Street, Carlisle, was prosecuted by Westmorland and Furness Council. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Dixon, pleaded guilty to the offence when he appeared at Carlisle Magistrates Court on November 26. \u00a0</p>\n\n\n\n<p>An environmental enforcement officer witnessed Dixon driving to a farm at Blencow, near Penrith, on July 11 2024, before loading scrap metal items onto his truck.\u00a0</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The council had previously warned Dixon about unlicensed collecting in 2020, but he informed the council officer that he had been collecting from the farm for years.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Councillor John Murray, cabinet member for transport and regulatory services, said: \u201cUnlicensed scrap metal collectors are unregulated and take trade away from those collectors who are licenced and regulated by the Council.\u00a0</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cThey can also use their activities to spot high value items in farmyards, or gardens, for future thefts.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cWe urge people to check in the windscreen of a scrap metal collector\u2019s vehicle to see if they have a Westmorland and Furness photo licence, before giving, or selling scrap to them.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>\u201cIt is not advisable to leave scrap metal items and white goods in front of your house as they may attract unscrupulous and illegal operators to your area.\u201d</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The council added that small, credit card-type identification cards carried by some unlicensed traders are not scrap metal licences and do not legally entitle anyone to collect scrap metal.</p>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
    excerpt: { rendered: '<p>A man has admitted collecting scrap metal without a licence and been fined by magistrates. </p>\n', protected: false },
