    title: { rendered: 'Eddie Stobart dies aged 95' },
    content: {
      rendered:
        '<div class="wp-block-image">\n<figure class="aligncenter size-full"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="599" height="331" src="https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Eddie-Stobart-lorry.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-11277" srcset="https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Eddie-Stobart-lorry.jpg 599w, https://cumbriacrack.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/Eddie-Stobart-lorry-300x166.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 599px) 100vw, 599px" /></figure></div>\n\n\n<p>Cumbrian haulage firm founder Eddie Stobart has died aged 95. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>His family announced today that Mr Stobart died on November 25. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The company was founded in 1946 and worked for farms and distributed fertiliser. In the 1970s, it expanded into becoming a logistics company focusing on road haulage, rail freight, and deep sea transport.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>In 1960, Mr Stobart bought his first lorry second-hand from the local garage, and had it repainted in post office red and Brunswick green.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The firm became iconic due to the HGVs &#8211; each of which was given a name. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The firm&#8217;s first three trucks were named Twiggy, after the 1960s model, Tammy Wynette, and Dolly Parton. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Mr Stobart was born in April 1929 in Cumbria. His family had a small holding at Hesket Newmarket.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>He married Nora Boyd in 1951, and they had four children &#8211; Anne, John,\u00a0Edward\u00a0and\u00a0William.\u00a0In their later years, Nora and Eddie lived in Scotby.</p>\n',
      protected: false,
    },
